            "id": "0f894b3e4f1d422ebcb95",
            "questionText": "In a hydroelectric power plant, water stored at a high elevation in a reservoir possesses substantial gravitational potential energy. This water then flows downwards from a height of $!$80 \\text{ m}$!$ to spin turbines that drive generators to produce electricity. The plant generates $!$150 \\text{ MW}$!$ of useful electrical power and operates with an overall efficiency of $!$85\\%$!$. Assuming the acceleration due to gravity is $!$9.8 \\text{ m/s}^2$!$, calculate the mass of water, in kilograms, that must flow through the turbines each second to maintain this power output.",
            "imageText": "A diagram of a hydroelectric power plant showing a reservoir, dam, pipes, turbines, and a generator building with transmission lines.",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "5a26e78ec1364b45a6e53",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the formula that gives the gravitational potential energy change of water falling from a height. Which of the following formulas correctly represents the change in gravitational potential energy?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "8af41638-67d0-4304-afe4-278a3e5c24b8"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta E_p = m \\cdot g \\cdot \\Delta h$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta E_p = \\frac{1}{2} m v^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta E_p = m \\cdot g / \\Delta h$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "3fb9d1e1242a4ab083f14",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now, before relating the potential energy to the power output, we need to consider the efficiency of the hydroelectric plant. Which formula correctly represents the efficiency in terms of useful energy output and total energy input?",
